page1.title: Property location
page1.description:
The Mount Lofty Ranges (MLR) is divided into twelve climate zones, which are areas of similar evapotranspiration and effective rainfall, being two key factors influencing crop water requirements.

For this part of the calculator select the suburb from the dropdown list. 

If the suburb is not listed then the property is not in the MLR and the water calculator cannot be used.

If the entire suburb is located within a single climate zone then only one climate zone will be displayed and must be selected.
If the suburb straddles two or more climate zones then use the [NatureMaps website](http://spatialwebapps.environment.sa.gov.au/naturemaps/?viewer=naturemaps&layerTheme=&scale=1155581.108577&basemap=&center=15471607.383525133%2C-4201320.038125619&layers=04zzJt0fZaDX0joCFv0UrNtQ0vVrAx3fmniy04R9wz0U0ZQW) to confirm which climate zone applies, then select the climate zone that encompasses all (or the greatest portion) of property. If the property is not located in the MLR then the water calculator cannot be used.
page1.tooltipSuburb: the suburb and climate zone must be selected before proceeding
page1.tooltipClimateZone: areas of similar crop water requirements

page2.title: Unlicensed water use
page2.description:
Unlicensed water use is water use where a water licence is not required. This includes household use, domestic gardens 0.4ha (4,000m2 or 1 acre) or smaller, firefighting reserve, chemical application on non-irrigated crops, and stock drinking water if the stock are not intensively farmed. 


Domestic garden areas can be measured using the Measure Tools function on the [NatureMaps website](http://spatialwebapps.environment.sa.gov.au/naturemaps/?viewer=naturemaps&layerTheme=&scale=1155581.108577&basemap=&center=15471607.383525133%2C-4201320.038125619&layers=04zzJt0fZaDX0joCFv0UrNtQ0vVrAx3fmniy04R9wz0U0ZQW).

Stock water requirements will vary widely among different types of animals.  It is also influenced by other factors such as animal age, type of feed (dry or green feed), production level and climate. The annual requirements for each broad type of animal is not based on peak requirements, but is based on the average daily intake for each stock category.

For advice regarding what constitutes unlicensed and licensed water use please call the Berri water licensing office on 8595 2053 or the Adelaide water licensing office on 8463 6876.
page2.labelFireFightingPump: Fire fighting reserve – fire pump and hoses used only
page2.labelFireFightingSprinkler: Fire fighting reserve – sprinkler system installed
page2.tooltipHousehold: Enter the number of dwellings on the property or properties.  This covers the water use inside the dwelling only (e.g. toilet, shower).
page2.tooltipGarden: Enter the irrigated area. The Garden is classified as domestic and exempt from requiring a licence only if the irrigated area does not exceed 0.4 hectares and is associated with a dwelling.  Water requirements for irrigated garden areas exceeding 0.4 hectares (and/or for gardens not associated with a dwelling) should be calculated using the “licensed water use for irrigation” step of the calculator.
page2.tooltipFireFightingRisk: Enter the number of dwellings for which fire fighting water is reserved
page2.tooltipFireFightingDwelling: Enter the number of dwellings for which fire fighting water is reserved
page2.tooltipWeedControl: Enter the area (hectares) of crop for which water was used for chemical application. The water requirement for chemical application for irrigated crops is included in the “licensed water use for irrigation” section of the calculator.
page2.tooltipStock: Enter the average number of stock (not intensively farmed) watered throughout the year, for each type of stock listed. For any stock type not listed, please use the “Other” category and enter your estimate of the annual water requirement for that type and number of stock.
page2.tooltipOther: Enter the estimated annual water requirement for any unlicensed water use not included above. Examples include swimming pool top-up, vehicle washdown, and chemical application for non-irrigated crops.

page3.title: Licensed water use for irrigation
page3.description:
For each climate zone in the Mount Lofty Ranges, the internationally recognised Food and Agricultural Organisation methodology (FAO Irrigation Paper No. 56) was used to determine how much water is theoretically needed for different crop types in an average season, assuming crops are grown for maximum production with no limiting conditions.  This does not apply to wine grapes and two pasture categories (low & standard production), where irrigation levels are controlled for quality reasons and specific production goals.


For this section of the calculator select the crop type from the drop-down list, and enter the number of hectares irrigated. Irrigated areas can be measured using the Measure Tools function on the [NatureMaps website](http://spatialwebapps.environment.sa.gov.au/naturemaps/?viewer=naturemaps&layerTheme=&scale=1155581.108577&basemap=&center=15471607.383525133%2C-4201320.038125619&layers=04zzJt0fZaDX0joCFv0UrNtQ0vVrAx3fmniy04R9wz0U0ZQW). This must be done for each crop type. For any crop not listed, please use the “Other” category and enter your estimate of the annual water requirement for that crop and area.
page3.headingTotal: Total estimated licensed water requirement for irrigation
page3.tooltipOtherCrop: Enter the crop name and the total estimated annual water requirement in kL

page4.title: Licensed water use for industrial and commercial purposes
page4.description:
The estimated water requirement for specific industrial or commercial water uses has been determined through consultation with key industry groups and using industry based information. 
For this part of the calculator, enter the number of units of production as shown in the tooltip. For any water use not listed, please use the “Other” category and enter your estimate of the annual water requirement..
page4.headingTotal: Total estimated licensed water requirement for industrial and commercial purposes
page4.tooltipOther: Enter the industrial/commercial activity and the total estimated annual water requirement in kL

page5.title: Summary and results
page5.description:
This section summarises the estimated annual water requirement based on the water purposes and crops entered. 

Note that 1 kilolitre (kL) = 1000 Litres or 220 gallons, and 1,000 kL = 1 Megalitre (ML) or 220,000 gallons.
page5.subheadingIndustrialAndCommercialWaterUs: Total estimated licensed water requirement for irrigation and/or industrial and commercial purposes
page5.descriptionWhatDoIDoNow:
This estimated water requirement information can be used to support property water planning, including:


• Broad understanding of total property water requirements.
• Evaluating water source reliability to match water requirements and understand any supply limitations.
• Planning for both current and future water requirements to match specific production goals.
• Monitoring water use for possible improvements in efficiencies and identification of surplus or shortfall in water.

For further information please return to the regional website <<links to be provided back to the water calculator webpage on the respective regional website>>

page5.disclaimer: Note that the data contained in this farm water calculator is provided for general information and should be used as a guide to your water requirement only. The information should not be used as the sole basis for decision making. You are advised to exercise due caution and seek independent professional advice before entering into any investment or financial obligation based on the results from using this water calculator. The water requirement for irrigation is based on maximum production (except in the case of Winegrape, Pasture – Low Production and Pasture – Standard Production), no limiting factors and average historic climatic conditions.
page5.finalNote:
This estimated water requirement information can be used to support property water planning, including:
* Broad understanding of total property water requirements.
* Evaluating water source reliability to match water requirements and understand any supply limitations.
* Planning for both current and future water requirements to match specific production goals.
* Monitoring water use for possible improvements in efficiencies and identification of surplus or shortfall in water.

For further information please return to the regional website.
